> > Here’s a simple example of conditional probability: say you wanted to know the probability of drawing a heart from a deck of cards. You know there are thirteen hearts in a standard fty-two-card deck, so your probability—P(heart), if you like—is 13/52, or 1/4. Or, in probability notation, p = 0.25. But then you draw a card, and it’s a club. What’s your probability now? Well, there are still thirteen hearts in the deck, but only fty-one cards in total. So your probability is now 13/51, or p ≈ 0.255. (The wavy equals sign means “approximately equal to.”) That’s the probability of drawing a heart given that you’ve previously drawn a club, P( heart ❘ Ace).
